note.p: Emendations attributed NLS Adv. MS 72.3.11 are by from a transcription of this text made by Donald Macintosh (1743-1808) in that MS on pp.1-27. This transcription shows taht damage to NLS Adv. MS 72.1.34 occurred subsequent to his transcription.

In Donald Mackintosh's (1743–1808) transcription of this text, writing appears after the word Lochlannach. IT reaches the edgeo of the page which is somewhat damaged at this time, thus making it difficult to be certain of the end of the word. The present transcriber/editor thinks that the text reads "an feachdnais". Check Ó Cróinín for this.

Although these MS pages were intact when Donald Macintosh had access to this text, his transcription is not always completely reliable. At times he mistakes letter forms, e.g. he takes the f in faithe (p.1, l.5) as an s. An exampe of where he is unsure what the text he is transcribing means occurs at p2, l.1 where the MS clearly reads 'chath do thuath de danann' but Macintosh has written 'is do chaidhe d. d.' (NLS Adv 72.3.11, p.1, l.16). Later in this text it becomes clear that Mac Pháill's t is often close to a d but upon closer examination they are in fact ts. Such an example can be found on p.2, l.5 where Macintosh writes 'do duit' for the MS's 'do tuit'. For this reason, the present editor postulates that the Mac Pháill wrote tuireadh rather than duiread in the original. Furthermore, Macintosh, who was using modern word spacing writes duireadna as a single entity, suggesting that he did not know it was two words and thus that he did not know what tuireadh was in this context.
As with the instance of tuireadh in l.2 it is likely that Mac Pháill wrote this word with an initial t.

Here Donald Macintosh (1748-1808) has something which appears to be a lowercase a with a somewhat rounded i ascending from the top left of the letter. Macintosh does not seem to have always understood the text and the present editor postulates that Ó Cróinín's interpretation of this, i.e. that don was originally written in the MS is correct as do is the preposition most freuently used with taobh elsewhere in this MS, e.g. p.2, l.4; p.5, ll.4, 5; p.17, ll.6, 9.

Ó Cróinín prints 'Clár Luighue' in his semi-diplomatic (p. 221, l.19) and diplomatic (p. 163, l.18) editions. In his notes (p. 180) he says 'Tá an litriú truaillithe anseo agus níor éirigh liom an logainm seo a aimsiú.' To the present editor, however, the form of the letter after the g appears to be clearly an n.

Regarding cruinnidur, (l.16), and dhainghnidur, here, Ó Cróinín says "Is ait liom na foirmeacha seo. Is briathra den dara réimniú iad seo agus ar an gcéad éachtaint is cosúil gur cuireadh sa chéad réimniú anseo iad. B'fhéidir gur sampla de hapology atá againn anseo .i. scríobhadh litir nó siolla amháin san áit a bhfuil dhá cheann ó cheart. Dá mba rud é go raibh chruinnidhidar agus do dhaingniudhadur os comhair an scríobhaí d'fhéadfadh sé dearmad a dhéanamh go fuirist agus gan ach id amháin a thabhairt leis ina thrascríbhinn. Is míniú sásúil é seo, dar liom, go háirithe nuair a chuirtear san áireamh go bhfuil dh agus gh meascaithe le chéile tríd síos sa lámhscríbhinn."

Ó Cróinín (pp.181-2) says '[..] tá seans go mbaineann sé seo le canúint an údair. B'fhéidir go léiríonn an litriú anseo canúint thusisceartach nó Albannach ach ba dheacair aon ahdmad ar leith a bhaint as an sampla seo toisc bacg bhfuil a thuilleadh samplaí sa téacs. Is deimhneach nach foirm liteartha í seo, áfach, agus is é is dealraithí ná gur éalaigh an fhoirm ó pheann an údair i ngan fhios dó.'

Ó Cróinín emends this to do bhéar (p.164) and notes (p.182) '[...] leasaíodh é seo ós rud é gur cosúil go bhfuil raibh [sic] mearbhall ar an scríobhaí idir an chéad agus an dara pearsa uatha anseo. Míodhach atá ga [sic] caint le Fionn anseo.' Ó Cróinín's aim was to produce a text that was 'soléite do léitheoir a bhfuil taithí aige ar an Nua-Ghaeilge' (p. 36). The different emmendation here is due to the present editor remaining as close to the original as possible, only emmending what is necessary for the text to make sense.
The -a in triucha here is supplied silently in Ó Cróinín's edited text (p.165).)
Ó Cróinín silently emends this to 'ar Thulach an Foirghleanna' (p.165). He does not give reason for this, nor does he indicate why he did not lenite Foirghleanna in this emendation.

Regarding this form, Ó Cróinín (p. 182) says 'Is é atá mar bhunús leis an bhfoirm réamhfhoclach fon anseo ná meascán idir dhá réamhfhocal na Sean-ghaeilge, fo agus imm (Féach [S.] Ó Ceoinín[, Lia Fáil (Baile Átha Cliath:] 1926).
Ó Cróinín has 'do dhearmad olc do' (pp. 167, 225).
Or: abfias = a bhios?
OR is it selgad, http://dil.ie/37057?

Ó Cróinín prints tren in the edited text (p. 169) and in the diplomatic edition (p. 227). While the present editor agrees with this interpretaition interpretaion they cannot see any trace of an n, nor indication in the manuscript of one having faded, been rubbed out or deleted.
Instead of ttionol Donald Macintosh (1743-1808) has 'da ttaitnadh an teannadh'.
In the MS sealga was written before suibhne but marks in the MS indicate that they should have been written in reverse order.

The MS is damaged here. As the end of the descender of the f and its cross stroke are still visible, and as the meaning is clear, it has been transcribed as an f. The damage extends to the second letter of the word which may have been an i or e. Due to the regularity with which Mac Pháill writes i in this name in this text it has here been taken as an i.
The word ceann does not appear in the MS yet Ó Cróinín supplies it without any indication that he has done so in his edited (p. 171) and diplomatic (p.229) texts.
Ó Cróinín gives this as "rí eile" in edited text (p.171) but Lochlann in "diplomatic" (p.230).
In the MS "da dorn is written before "cuid" but marks in the MS denote that the two should swap places.
WG, ET, what do you think? This HW is the best I could do but it may not be correct.
Donald_Macintosh_(1743-1808) writes 'da cois amhulad anochda'.
NEW GLYPH NUMBER USED - URR OR UIRR?
Ó Cróinín silently supplies the fh here, both in the "diplomatic" and edited texts.

The scribe may have intended to write eolachtach, or something akin to it, or may have accidentally indicated the end of the word with both a suspension stroke-lenition dot combination and then written out plene. As the present editor has no other examples of eolachtach the reading has been emended to eolach.
Is ScG madh from OIr mám? The HW here is the ScG not the OIr because I wasn't 100% on it.

Before both righ and feinnidh here the letters a that have been emended out of the edition are in superscript. In other cases where we find use of superscript a, we find a corresponding b to indicate that the reader should change the order from that written on the page. In this case, however, reading feinnidh before righ would not make sense. Perhaps mac Pháill thought a correction was to be made and noted a superscript a before righ but subsequently saw that he had written the text correctly and opted to confirm this by also writing a superscript a before feinnidh, or perhaps these have another purpose unknown to the present editor.

note.p: Black (0002498)says that "The form geubhadh seems to be required both metrically [and] morphologically. Probably a suspension stroke has simply been omitted."
Black (0110468) says that the form obar is required for rhyme with cogar."
Black supplies this in the HDSG slip for this line (0030416).
If not furthain, maybe a form of airrinde, http://dil.ie/2371? Black (0131226) did not know the meaning of this word.
